@NODE "About" "About the group"

  @{b}@{u}About@{uu}@{ub}

History....By DamNation

Instinct originally started way back in early 1993, when they was called
"Technological Expressions". This was a solo group, based in Edinbugh,
Scotland, with the one member (me), without as alias. I did graphics, wrote
mods and put together the odd self-booting disk. All I had was a 1MB A500+
with one disk drive and a 9pin Dot Matrix printer. Nothing was really 
released, apart from a few mods to a small PD company.

Around 1995, T.E changed to "T.4.2" (Techno For Two). One of my friends
(who had a PC) provided samples and mods and although I mainly wrote most of
the mods, he helped give advice and other bits. I was now known as Android
(groan) and he was Jimbob. Again, not much was released, but when I got 
access to the Internet in mid 1995 (via a CyberCafe), I sent a few
of my best mods to date to a few people on IRC. Nothing continued to grow,
but mods steadily got written.

Then, in September 1995, T.4.2 moved to Auckland New Zealand, returning the
group to a solo state again. The odd mod was written, but nothing much, as
I didn't get access to my Amiga until it arrived at our house in NZ some 3
months later.

In December 1995, I finally took a leap and got myself an A1200 with a 40MB
HD. Then the mods started improving, as I wasn't limited to mods no bigger
than 500K. My first mod written on then A1200 was a remix of Altern-8's
"Frequency", but the sequencing really sucked, so I never finished it
properly. Progress continued until March 1996, when I got a 4MB upgrade
card. Now my mods could be even better, and I started churning out higher
quality tunes. 

When April 1996 came, I finally got myself a Modem, and an Internet
account. That is when the group got changed to Instinct (still solo)
and I changed my alias to DamNation. Some problems arose from this alias,
as I later found out that when I changed my name, a few months previously,
an Amiga warez BBS called "Damnation" has just closed down, and people
thought I was the sysop of that BBS! Anyway, I uploaded a few of my recent
mods to some BBSs, and to my suprise, some of them have been spread further
than I thought!

And so, as I became more familar with the Internet, I grew towards IRC
(doesn't everyone?) and one cold August evening, in the #amigacafe Undernet
channel, I got talking to a guy called Hyper, who wrote Techno mods and had
released a few tunes on Aminet. We continued to talk, and eventually, I
asked him if he was in a group. He said no, but he would like to. He shortly
joined the group, and became Hyper/Instinct UK :)

A new IRC channel was set up by me, Demoulous and Stoo, regular IRC users.
We called our channel #modulez, and out intention was to get to a buzz of
Music Module news, trading and swapping going on Undernet. This seemed to
go OK at the beginning, but the channel wasn't advertised enough, and
no-one seemed to join the channel unless either me, Hyper or the above guys
were in the channel to give it a bit of a boost.

Then, early in September 1996, I lost my account with my ISP, because of
important exams coming up, and having a slight suspicion my ISP was
overcharging me. I told Hyper to continue looking after the group whilst I
was away, so I'll leave the next bit to Hyper himself to give the lowdown:

Hyper continues...

OK, so now there was still only two people in the group. I continued to use
IRC whilst DamN was away in the hope that I could find some talented people
willing to join up. It wasn't long until I met a chap called Maggotman. I
found out that he liked to do the odd bit of 3D GFX and stuff with lightwave
and he gave me the URL of his homepage. I checked it out and I was amazed!,
"Hey, this guy is brilliant" I thought, "this guy has gotta belong to a 
group.". I asked if he did and it turned out that he didn't. I couldn't
believe my luck and I asked him if he wanted to be in one. He had a good
think about it and then said "Yes!". I was really happy about it, the next
thing I knew was that he had been asked by Fairlight UK to do a logo for
them, he did one, but wasn't happy with it even tho I thought it was kewl.
I dunno, thats perfectionists for ya isn't it? :) Anyway he said that he
wouldn't even be interested in joining Fairlight and that he would be 
staying with us.

The next person that joined while DamNation was away was Wulf. I'd known
him for a little while from IRC and as I got to know more about the
sort of things that he could do(eg hacking and programming) I thought
that he could be of use to us. He asked if we wanted him in the group,
I though "Why not?" and that made four of us. Check out his "Hex"
program which is available via his web site.

Just before DamNation left he met a chap called Amorel, he'd been doing
oldskool techno mods for quite a while with many of them being on Aminet.
DamNation had asked him if he wanted to join but we'd had no answer for
a while. Amorel eventually said yes to joining and he was then made a
member.

OK, thats all that I got up to, I'll now pass you back to DamNation.

DamNation returns...

Eventually, in December 1996, I got a new Internet account, and was back on
the net. When I finally met up with Hyper, he told me that Instinct now had
a (sort of) Homepage, along with a homepage for #modulez. I had been told
that CService had taken #modulez off Undernet due to inactivity, but it was
relaunched, and hopefully if the word gets around, the channel would start
to grow a bit more...

Also, while I was away, 3 new members has joined Instinct, these were:

Wulf: Norway - Trader, part-time coder and general nutter.
MaGGoTMaN: Australia - Graphics and other bits.
Amorel: Holland - Musician, although we haven't heard much fron him recently.
(hence why I have not put any of his mods in the Instinct File Support Area
on the BBS yet).

Then, in early January, a guy who had been close with the members of
Instinct and also a composer of some excellent (normally non Techno) mods
joined the group. Hyper and I thought his talent was going to waste being
solo, so we snatched him up! His name is Mr Lou, and he is from Denmark.
You can now find all his mods in the File Support area on the BBS.

A musician called Chill joined soon after, he'd done many kewl mods in the
past so we decided to snap him up. We'd met him in #modulez, he was
previously in a group called "Neuro" but this group was slowly dying off 
with him being the only really active member.

Instinct continues to spread across Europe...and beyond!!

